               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc ana="#slab">
                     <!-- describe the text-bearing object, its condition and history here -->
                     <supportDesc ana="#stone.marble">
                        <support>
                           <seg type="material">marble</seg>
                           <seg type="form"></seg>
                           <p>Thick marble slab with handle cut out on the left side.The handle measures 23x6 cm. It is oval at the top but is turned down at the bottom edges, which also show some signs of wear. Tool marks are visible inside the handle. The back of the slab is roughly chiseled for bonding. There are also light traces of gray plaster.</p><!-- QUESTION: should this <p> element be nested within <seg type="form">? For some reason I have the <seg> elements nested within a larger <p> -->
                              <dimensions type="surface" unit="cm">
                                 <width>61.6</width>
                                 <height>36.1</height>
                                 <depth>6.0</depth>
                              </dimensions>
                        </support>
                        <condition ana="#complete.broken"><!-- QUESTION: OR is it #fragments.contig? After all, the right handle is missing....-->
                           <p>The top left corner of the tablet (containing D. and the top part of the handle) has broken off the remainder of the tablet. Additionally, the right-hand side of the tablet is not fully intact - while the main text has been preserved, the M. is only partially visible.</p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" writtenLines="8">
                           <p>The majority of the text (7 lines) is located within a thinly incised frame. D. M. is placed in the margins outside of this frame. These two letters, comparable in size to the rest of the text, are positioned in the top right and left hand corners, respectively, and are equidistant from the frame. The top of each letter lies on the same horizontal axis as the top part of the frame. Guide lines are visible in the main body of text, which is largely well laid out <!-- SUGGESTION: "evenly laid out" since there's no value judgement attached to that; also, suggest "campus" to describe the field where the writing is. -->(barring the final line, which ends halfway across). </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc ana="#impressed.inscribed.chiseled">
                     <handNote> D.
                        <height unit="cm">2.8cm</height>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote> M.
                        <height unit="cm">2.4cm</height>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote> P-longa in line 2<!-- QUESTION: You mean line one?-->
                        <height unit="cm">3.5cm</height>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote> Other letter heights line 2
                        <height unit="cm" min="2.5" max="2.8">2.5cm - 2.8cm</height>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote> Letter heights, line 3
                        <height unit="cm" min="2.2" max="2.5">2.2cm - 2.5cm</height>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote> Letter height, lines 4-6
                        <height unit="cm">3.0cm</height>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote> Letter heights, lines 7-8
                        <height unit="cm" min="2.5" max="2.7">2.5cm - 2.7cm</height>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote ana="blank">
                        <p> While the hand is largely consistent (the letters are generally spaced evenly and of a similar dimension), there is some variation in lettering, which is especially visible in the rendering of the letter M. Variety is also visible in the appearance of the interpuncts (slashes and points are both present) and they do not have a consistent depth, though this may be the product of wear on the surface. The hederae (discussed below) are likewise not consistent. However, there is no clear evidence for suggesting that this epitaph is the product of multiple hands.</p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote ana="#blank">
                        <p> At the end of each of the first two lines of the main body of text within the incised frame, there is a hedera. These "hederae" are irregular and inconsistent in shape. While they are roughly the same size (3.3cm vs. 3.5cm measured on the diagonal), the first hedera is topped with a hook curving to the left, while the second remains straight. There are also small traces of paint visible.</p>
                     </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
